bug.short_desc: [launcher] Issue with cached library jars in user's workspace after updating with Webstart

long_desc.thetext: i get the same problem described in http://dev.eclipse.org/newslists/news.eclipse.platform.rcp/msg06378.html

There seems to be a larger issue here.
It seems like in WebStart we have the bundle jars directly replaced and no uninstall/update/install process occurs to tell the framework that the bundle has changed. This effects more than just the cached libraries contained in a bundle. We also cache information from the bundle's manifest (bundle symbolic name, bundle version, exported packages etc.), if this information changes in a new jar we will not recognize the new data. One way to work around this issue would be to set the following property.
osgi.checkConfiguration=true
This will cause the framework to check the timestamp of the bundle jar, if it has changed then it will throw the old data away and force the new version of the bundle to be installed. Please let us know if setting this property helps you work around the issue. Thanks.

right now my workaround is the osgi.clean=true property. is it better to use osgi.checkConfiguration=true instead of osgi.clean=true? i found no documentation about osgi.checkConfiguration.
but imho a workaround is not the solution of a problem...

The osgi.checkConfiguration is used by PDE to help with self-hosting, in the past this has been an internal API. As such this option has not been documented. But IMO we should document all our options.
osgi.checkConfiguration is better than always using osgi.clean. You should have better startup performance with osgi.checkConfiguration because we do not throw away the complete cache like we do with osgi.clean. It only throws away content from updated bundles.
This is not a solution. But it should be an acceptable workaround until we can think of a good solution. I do not know that much about WebStart so we will have to wait for Pascal to see what his thoughts are for a solution.
We should investigate a fix for M7. At this point the only acceptable fix for 3.3 is probably to set osgi.checkConfiguration=true in WebStartMain if it is not already set.

bug.short_desc: [move method] "Move method" results in improper cast
[console] Shutdown does not respect bundle start levels

long_desc.thetext:
The "shutdown" command (and similarly, "close") does not perform the proper OSGi shutdown sequence. What OSGi R4 Core 8.2.4 says about the shutdown sequence: "When the Framework shuts down, the requested start level must be set to zero. The Framework must then follow the process described in Changing the Active Start Level on page 197 to make the active start level equal to zero."
As I understand, this means that the framework must start decreasing the active start level until it reaches zero. What actually happens is that bundles get stopped in an unknown order (possibly the order in which they were installed, but I haven't checked).
For example one of my bundles (start level 4) depends on preferences service in "org.eclipse.equinox.preferences" (which I set to start level 1) while stopping. Stopping works properly when I do "setfwsl 1", but with "shutdown" or "close" the "org.eclipse.equinox.preferences" bundle is stopped first.

I tested this again in a new workspace. At first I created two simple Hello World bundles. Both of them were started and stopped in the correct order. Then I added a dependency on the package "org.osgi.services.prefs" to one of the bundles and added all the required bundles to the launch configuration (giving the preferences bundle a lower starlevel than the others). And it happened again: on "close" or "shutdown" the preferences bundle was stopped before my bundle, even though it's start level was lower.
Should I attach the sample workspace, it's 3MB (I don't know which metadata is ok to delete before the launch configuration is lost)?

Bugzilla will likely not allow you to attach a 3 MB workspace. I would suggest that you:
- Saved your launch configuration into a .launch file as a "Shared file" by putting it in one of your projects. Do this from the Run dialog's Common page.
- Export your projects into a zip and attach it to this bug report. I typically disconnect from CVS and delete all the CVS metadata before doing this. Once the projects have been imported back into Eclipse the .launch file will be detected by Eclipse and added to the Run dialog.
- Update the bug report with any necessary steps to recreate the bug.

Created an attachment (id=47400) Workspace to reproduce the bug
Use the projects & launch config in this zip to reproduce the bug.

Import the projects in the attachement, run the "ShutdownExample" launch configuration.
The console should print: osgi> Bundle A Starting Bundle B Starting PreferencesService does exist.
Execute the "close" command. Now the console prints:
Bundle B Stopping PreferencesService does not exist. Bundle A Stopping
If everything worked correctly, it should print "PreferencesService does exist." the second time as well.

I saw that org.eclipse.core.internal.adaptor.EclipseAdaptorHook is stopping some bundles (in public void frameworkStopping(BundleContext), lines 155 & 156) before the start level starts to decrease. Maybe I'm really off course here but it seems to me that it should not stop the bundles there because Equinox implements the start level service.
The last sentence in the OSGi R4 Core 4.7.2 Shutdown, 2. action in the list: "If the Framework implements the optional Start Level specification, this behavior is different. See Start Level Service Specification on page 195."

Preferences bundle is a lazy-start bundle (contains the Bundle-LazyStart manifest header). This means it is activated the first time a class is loaded from it. Lazy loaded bundles need to be shutdown in a reverse dependency order so that they do not attempt to load classes from other lazy-start bundles that have already been stopped. Upon shutdown we ensure that lazy-started bundles are deactivated in the proper order before we start decrementing the framework start-level.
Normal bundles should be able to handle this if they are properly listening for when services come and go from the system.
This is working as designed.

So it's not possible to get the preferences while stopping a normal bundle?
My bundle needs to read some preferences (while stopping) to know how to connect to a database server and persist some objects. I should then read the preferences earlier, cache them and rely on cached, possibly stale data on stopping?

I suggest you listen for when the preferences service is unregistered and save your data then (Using a ServiceListener or ServiceTracker). This is recommended because in OSGi a service may be unregistered at anytime, not just when the bundle providing the service is stopped.
Another option is to listen for when the the System Bundle is STOPPING, using a SynchronousBundleListener. The System Bundle always has a bundle ID of 0. The framework will post a BundleEvent.STOPPING for the system bundle before the shutdown process begins. This event is posted before the lazy started bundles are stopped. While this will work today, I still recommend the first approach becuase theoretically the preferences service may be unregistered at anytime.

bug.short_desc: Static analysis features for CDT

long_desc.thetext:
Building upon the "ASTVisitor enhancement to enable bottom-up traversal" enhancement - bugzilla https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=152846
We are building and hope to contribute to CDT: 1. Call graph implementation 2. Control flow graph implementation 3. Dominator information available at every control flow graph node Defn: Node d of a flow graph "dominates" node n, written "d dom n", if every path from the initial node of the flow graph to n goes through d. 4. Def-Use (DU) chains for scalar variables (excluding pointers) where arrays and structures are treated as a single scalar unit. DU chains connect the definition of a variable with all its uses.
We also provide two ways to traverse the control flow graph and the call graph -- topological order and reverse topological order. We can also recognize recursive calls in the call graph. These are not big points, but very handy for analysis purpose.
Our current implementation only handles C programs, not C++ .
Discussion welcome.

bug.short_desc: Can't load registered resource into ecore if that resource is in dev workspace

long_desc.thetext:
On an ecore, you can choose to load another model by browsing the registered packages, but the only available packages are ones that are in the target environment and do not included registered packages from the dev workspace.
To reproduce (see attached projects): - Note that the project TestEmfProject1 has a registered model with uri "testpackage1.xmi". That is, the plugin includes the location for the genmodel in the extension. - Open the model "test2.ecore" in project TestEmfProject2 - Right click on top node and "Load Resource..." - Note that the uri "testpackage1.xmi" is not in the list
The model *can* be loaded by hand (text edit) and everything works fine.

Created an attachment (id=47403) EmfTestProjects.zip
This includes two projects (as described in bug description) TestEmfProject1 and TestEmfProject2

It's intended that it provide access those packages registered via the extension point in the target workspace. You can use "Browse Workspace" for accessing models that are in the development workspace...

Here's the problem with that. We're creating a model for the intended purpose of extension by other users. And we're loading another resource that we have created to help with that. If extenders use our first resource by way of the plugin route, then the referenced resource cannot be resolved. We need to develop our primary model with our secondary model referred to as a *plugin* resource, so that extenders won't have this problem.
The ecore model works well like this, and gives us our desired behavior. The UI should work like this as well. It's only a matter of adding workspace items to the chooser. I don't understand why this is so quickly marked a "won't fix". It's a trivial bug.

Paul,
The real problem is that I don't understand the real problem. To start you describe an issue you have with something that's working exactly as designed (it's supposed to open only registered packages from the target environment) and you also ask for the ability to do something that's already supported (you can open Ecore resources in the workspace). In general, you should expect a quick resolution, one way or the other, for an issue like this, the same as with any other issues that come our way. I'm quite sure it's not the quick resolution that concerns you but rather that it's not resolved to your liking. You describe the problem as trivial, but I wonder if that means you have the solution to contribute, i.e., you could provide the trivial patch to fix it...
In your latest comments, you make more clear that your concern is related to the specific URI used to open the resource, but I'll point out that the dialog already allows you to enter any URI you might want to type in, so no capability is missing that prevents you from achieving your desired result. What I don't understand is the basis for your concern about platform:/plugin verses platform:/resource. The resource really is in the workspace and using the platform:/resource URI is the appopriate thing to use for resources in the workspace. All serialized references to such a resource from other Ecore resources within the workspace will use relative URIs that will work equally well later when all the resources are packaged as plugins. We rely heavily on this fact to support the development time versions of the Ecore artifacts in the runtime exactly as they appear at development time.
You mention having, in your specific situation, an Ecore resource that references some other resource. The serialized form of these references seem to cause you issues when the resource is used in the Ecore workspace. But it seems to me that the same problem will then arise when you try to open that Ecore resource directly within the workspace (i.e., double clicking the resource), not just when you try to reference it from some other resource. Can you explain with a detailed example why this additional non-Ecore reference is a problem so that I can understand better why you are asking for something that appears completely unnecessary and also seems subject to introducing additional confusion.
At this point my sense is that the serialized form of your non-Ecore reference is the real root of the problem and that you are trying to solve it by insisting on an a feature enhancement in the Ecore editor. But I'd expect these non-Ecore references to work just as well as do the Ecore references, and I'll need a good understanding of why that's not the case before I'll make changes in the tools to accomodate that.

Ed, the only thing that really concerns me is that you haven't taken the time to understand the issue, and have instead chosen to cast off user input.
It boils down to this. I want to code my extendable plugin "Plugin A" in such a way that it is usable by others. I am also using Plugin A in another plugin "Plugin B", and *by* using Plugin A in Plugin B, I hope to replicate the user experience. As such, I want all references to Plugin A in Plugin B to be *non resource* references. I want to access Plugin A in only ways that other developers would access it, and in ways that do not require loading the project for Plugin A into their dev workspace. I have tested and know that specifying "ecore A" as a dependent resource in "ecore B" as a *plugin* resource, that is by specifying referenced types in the ecore as such: eType="ecore:EClass ../../../plugin/TestEmfProject1/model/test1.ecore#//TestClass1"
and not as such: eType="ecore:EClass ../../TestEmfProject1/model/test1.ecore#//TestClass1"
and by specifying genmodel references in the genmodel as such: usedGenPackages="../../../plugin/TestEmfProject1/model/test1.genmodel#//testpackage1"
and not as such: usedGenPackages="../../TestEmfProject1/model/test1.genmodel#//testpackage1"
*works*. What does not work is either the ability to see that registered package when I browse or typing in the URL for that registered package in the browse dialog. It seems to me to be a simple UI, thing, but if it's not, I bow to your judgement. I hope you can assure me that by referencing Plugin A as a *resource* from Plugin B, it will still work for users of Plugin B *when Plugin B in the target platform and not in the dev workspace*.

Paul,
Based on our private discussions ;-) I think you're okay if we resolve this as works for me.
Thanks again for taking the time to raise issues and for understanding that while we occassionally handle issues a little more abuptly than would be ideal, we certainly intend to remain responsive to any followup discussions.

bug.short_desc: Parse bytecode at most once when weaving: 10% CPU time reduction

long_desc.thetext:
I'm analyzing a profile of cpu times spent weaving into Weblogic 9.2 with LTW. Of a total of 22 seconds of CPU, 2.6 seconds are spent in ClassParser.parse() with the exact same amount spent underneath WeavingAdaptor.shouldWeave and WeavingAdaptor.shouldWeaveAnnotationStyleAspect
WeavingAdaptor.shouldWeave is calling CLWA.accept which calls Utility.makeJavaClass which calls ClassParser.parse. Then the exact same expensive operation is getting called again in shouldWeaveAnnotationStyleAspect via BcelWorld.isAnnotationStyleAspect.
Proposed Simple fix: allow shouldWeave to also return a BcelObjectType by setting a field in the adapter (which would be cleared to be null on start). The in shouldWeaveAnnotationStyleAspect, check the field. I'd be glad to write and test a patch to do this if the committers agree with the proposal.
We wouldn't want to always parse the bytecode, because it would we should be aiming to avoid that expense as often as possible. In our case, we're using exclusion type patterns that currently require accept to make a Java class. In cases where that's not necessary, it also seems odd that shouldWeaveAnnotationStyleAspect runs at all: I will post a separate enhancement request for limiting the cases where it runs.

In addition, as Alex's comments in ClassLoaderWeavingAdaptor.accept indicate, if the class is accepted, then the bytecode will get parsed a third time in the constructor for WeavingClassFileProvider. So this too should use the already parsed Java class, if any.

... and then again in BcelWeaver.weave where classFile.getClassName() also parses it. In the test configuration I described before another 300 ms is spent parsing again in WeavingClassFileProvider and another 400 ms is spent parsing in UnwovenClassFile.getJavaClass. That brings the total CPU time overhead from redundant parsing to over 10% in this configuration.

This bug is related to Bug 152873. However we should be able to determine more efficiently, perhaps by looking at the set of registered aspects, whether a particular class is in fact an @AspectJ aspect thereby eliminating one of the duplicate parses.

bug.short_desc: Optimize shouldWeaveAnnotationStyleAspect with Patch

long_desc.thetext:
The current implementation of shouldWeaveAnnotationStyleAspect is surprising because it weaves annotation aspects without regard as to whether they are registered in an aop.xml file. If an annotation-style aspect is loaded, it is always woven, even if it doesn't match the for what classes should be woven in the aop.xml file, and even if not registered therein. This is both unexpected and it imposes significant overhead on configurations where they aren't used and simple fast match exclusions prevent weaving (see bug #152871).
Is there really a need to weave annotation style aspects like this? Why can't it be done by using the aop.xml configuration mechanism that all other aspects use? In a large system, the CPU overhead of parsing and creating BCEL objects for all loaded classes should be avoided where possible.

not my code ... but I believe they have to be included in the weaving because they may be half finished (have no aspectOf/hasAspect). Hence they are not subject to the same rules as regular code styles aspects that are always already finished.
You might well exclude them at some level but if they are included at a different level and *do* apply then that code will be woven with calls to aspectOf() that will go bang unless the @AJ aspect was finished off by getting woven when first discovered.

It is possible, through the use of a custom IWeavingContext for example, to include an aspect for a weaver that was excluded by another visible aop.xml file. In which case the locally defined classes will be woven with an unfinished aspect and get NoSuchMethodError for aspectOf(). We therefore cannot exclude @AspectJ aspects and should issue a warning message if the user attempts to do so either by using either include or exclude in the weaver section.

It looks like avoiding this check altogether would be hard. However, the main objective here is to reduce the time spent testing for annotation-style aspects. Eugene Kuleshov wrote a simple ASM visitor that I adapted and plugged in, and I also avoided testing for annotation aspects in classes like javax..* that can't be woven. This patch should also be a bit faster when AspectJ uses ASM 3.0, so it could add flags to skip parsing methods and fields too (I tested short-circuitng those tests by throwing a runtime exception but that was actually slower).
The attached patch contains tests that validate this logic works both for excluded @Aspect annotations and that it doesn't match for other annotations.
I have measured that this patch reduces cpu time used in shouldWeaveAnnotationStyleAspect when starting WebLogic from over 1000 ms to 200 ms (an 80% reduction in overhead and a 10% reduction in total weaving time).
Longer term, I think it should be a requirement that an annotation-style aspect should always be listed with an aspect element in an aop.xml configuration visible to its loader. That seems much better than having to parse the bytecode of all loaded types to see if they are, in fact, an annotation-style aspects.
If such a rule were agreed upon then it would be important to not allow including aspects that aren't woven to avoid a NoSuchMethodError from unfinished aspects. Unfortunately, it seems like doing this would require weaver context support so you could determine if the aspect class is loaded by this loader or not. In the former case, simply requiring the aspect to not be excluded (as Matthew noted) and if there's a non-empty inclusion list requiring the aspect to be in that would work. If we could determine the aspect is provided by an external loader, then we could instantiate a reflection delegate for it and test that it had the required woven methods. Maybe when #133770 is fixed we can revisit this. In the meanwhile, this patch dramatically reduces the overhead for annotation-style aspects.

bug.short_desc: [performance] BundleLoader.initialize has O(n2) algorithm

long_desc.thetext: This is quite a biggy for my product, so I increased the severity.

More data: When using a HashSet instead of an ArrayList, I see ~2 million method calls. When I use an ArrayList, but remove the expensive "contains" call, I see 1.2 million method calls.
How prevalent are export package lists with duplicates? Can we leave the responsibility to clean up manifest files to consumers of the framework?

Created an attachment (id=47439) patch
I assume you want this fixed in 3.2.1?
There is a tiny corner case in the OSGi spec that forces us to do this extra bit of work. The spec actually allows for a bundle to export the same package multiple times with different directives/attributes. bundles can use the include, exclude and x-friends directives to act as filtering directives on an exported package. The can then export a package multiple times and filter out different classes for different importers. In the Require-Bundle case the requiring bundle only sees the first export of the package.
Under normal scenarios we create package sources lazily, but in cases where exclude, include or x-friends is used we create them early so that we don't have to remember all the directive information later when we are creating normal package sources. Keep in mind that ExportPackageDescriptions can be flushed from memory so we do not want to pin these objects.
This is why we are checking for duplicates in initialize, because we do not want to force the creating of a package source unless it is the first export of that package name AND it has one of the special directives. This patch does two things
- it uses a HashSet if the number of exports > 10 otherwise it uses ArrayLists. Chris, do you have any recomendations on when it is better to use a HashSet vs ArrayList? For example, I know HashSets take up way more memory than ArrayLists even when it has very few elements. Is there a general recommendation when you know the number of elements, which is better?
- It checks for the special directives before checking for duplicates. A vast majority of packages will not have the directives so this should eliminate all calls to Collection.contains under normal conditions.
Chris can you try this patch out. Thanks.

I verified the patch. I had a slightly different version of org.eclipse.osgi, but manual patching worked. I am seeing the fastest startup times I have ever seen with this patch. About 200ms faster to get to "Starting Application" and about 400ms faster to get to "Application Started".
Your logic for arraylist when <10 seems very reasonable to me. I would have done it the same way :-) HashSet element have quite some overhead.
+1 for this patch.
I would like to see this patch in 3.2.1

On a bit larger scenario, I see startup time improving from 7.2s to 6.4s on average. This is a huge 11% improvement!
Now, if I can stop people from resolving DNS names on the UI thread, which easily adds 2s to 10s to the startup time, I can claim success on my product's overall startup goals :-)
This patch made my weekend. I'll be humming all week.
I released the patch in time for 3.3 M1 to get more testing. Jeff, please approve for 3.2.1.

bug.short_desc: [DetachedView] Detached Views Should Not Be Marked Transient

long_desc.thetext:
Detached views/windows in Eclipse are demonstrably not transient: they are saved and restored across changes in perspective (whether or not they should be cleared across perspective changes is the subject of another bug report), and they're even saved and restored across invocations of Eclipse. However, on my Linux system, they're apparently marked as transient windows and do not have windo titles attached.
Whether or not this is a problem depends, in part, on your window manager, and how you use it. I use FVWM, and the current detached windows are difficult to resize, move, find in a menu of current windows, etc. Turning on transient window decorations helps, but still doesn't supply a menu.
I've filed this report in Platform/UI, as have other posters on other detached view problem. The solution might involve SWT changes, though, in order to control the X window transient flag and supply a window title to detached views.

This is likely intentional...see bug 96428. If we expose the detached windows as 'top-level' shells then a variety of other issues come into play...
I'm not exactly sure what the word 'transient' means here...is it Linux/GTK jargon (perhaps a style bit set by SWT) ?
